Infrastructure Design

When a user types www.foobar.com
, the DNS resolves it to the IP of a load balancer cluster (two HAproxy servers). This setup improves availability in case one load balancer fails.

The load balancers distribute incoming requests to multiple web servers (Nginx). These web servers only handle HTTP/HTTPS requests and serve static content.

Dynamic requests are forwarded to separate application servers, which handle the application logic and process user requests.

The application servers communicate with a dedicated database server (MySQL), which manages and stores all the data.

Why we added these components
Additional server: to handle more traffic and improve performance
Second load balancer (cluster): to remove the single point of failure at the load balancer level
Separated components (web, app, database): to improve scalability, performance, and maintainability
Application server vs Web server
Web server (Nginx): handles client requests, serves static files, and forwards dynamic requests
Application server: processes business logic and interacts with the database
Summary

This architecture improves:

Scalability (can handle more users)
High availability (no single point of failure in load balancer)
Performance (each component has its own role)
